      SPARC SPARC SPARCWe  talked on Friday about Pershing Square Tontine H=
oldings Ltd., Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s special purpose acquisition vehicle, wh=
ich will fission into three SPAC-like things: It will do a somewhat SPAC-is=
h deal with Universal Music Group BV and distribute Universal shares to its=
 investors, it will keep some cash around in a =E2=80=9CRemainco=E2=80=9D t=
hat will try to do another acquisition, and, most interestingly, it will em=
it a SPARC. Pershing Square explains:SPARC is not a SPAC. It is a Special P=
urpose Acquisition Rights Company. Unlike a traditional SPAC, SPARC does no=
t intend to raise capital through an underwritten offering in which investo=
rs commit capital without knowing the company with which SPARC will combine=
.Instead, SPARC intends to issue rights to acquire common stock in SPARC fo=
r $20.00 per share to PSTH shareholders (=E2=80=9CSPARs=E2=80=9D) which can=
 only be exercised after SPARC enters into a definitive agreement for its i=
nitial business combination.Pershing Square Tontine Holdings will distribut=
e the SPARs =E2=80=94=C2=A0the SPARC rights =E2=80=94=C2=A0to its existing =
shareholders, so they can have first dibs on the next big deal that Ackman =
does. As I said on Friday, this strikes me as a cool idea. For one thing, i=
t is in some ways a better product, for investors, than a SPAC: Instead of =
locking up money for up to two years while a SPAC hunts for a deal (and the=
n maybe taking it back if they don=E2=80=99t like the deal), SPARC investor=
s don=E2=80=99t put up any money until the SPARC finds a deal.[1]For anothe=
r thing, though, right now is kind of a hard time to raise money for a SPAC=
: There are a lot of SPACs, there is a lot of money tied up in them, a lot =
of them have not traded that well, and there is a general sense that the ea=
rly-2021 frenzy for SPACs left the market oversaturated. The Pershing Squar=
e SPARC lets Ackman go out and hunt for a $4 billion deal=C2=A0without rais=
ing $4 billion, yet.[2] If he finds a company he likes, he can say =E2=80=
=9Cwell I=C2=A0more or less=C2=A0have a $4 billion pool of capital here.=E2=
=80=9D And then he can negotiate a deal and=C2=A0go to the SPARC holders fo=
r money, and if they like the deal they=E2=80=99ll give it to him.=C2=A0Let=
=E2=80=99s say you agree with me, and Ackman, that the SPARC is a good idea=
, and you want to launch one. How do you do that? Ackman is doing it as par=
t of this fissioning of PSTH: He already has a $4 billion SPAC, and he=E2=
=80=99s going to turn it into a $4 billion SPARC plus some other stuff (Uni=
versal, Remainco). If=C2=A0you=C2=A0also already have a SPAC, you could pro=
bably turn it into a SPARC too. I mean, probably best to fission it into a =
SPAC deal=C2=A0plus=C2=A0a SPARC, like Ackman is doing, though yours doesn=
=E2=80=99t have to be so complicated. Like:=09You have a SPAC.=09The SPAC d=
oes a regular SPAC deal, a =E2=80=9Cde-SPAC merger=E2=80=9D in which it mer=
ges with some private company to take it public.=09The SPAC says =E2=80=9Cw=
hen this SPAC deal closes, investors in the SPAC will get (1) shares of the=
 new public company that results from the SPAC deal=C2=A0plus=C2=A0(2) one =
right in my new SPARC.=E2=80=9D=09The SPAC closes, the new public company d=
oes its thing, and the new SPARC exists and trades.=09Eventually the SPARC =
finds another deal, goes to its rights holders and says =E2=80=9Cokay do yo=
u want to put in your money now?=E2=80=9D=09If they do, the SPARC closes an=
other deal.=09Might as well spin=C2=A0a new SPARC out of that one too.=09Et=
c.That is, the SPARC works as sort of a chain-SPARCing mechanism: You raise=
 a SPAC, and when the SPAC terminates in a successful deal you spin out a n=
ew SPARC; when that terminates in a successful deal it spins out another SP=
ARC; etc. Plenty of serial SPAC sponsors do something like this =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0raise a new SPAC after successfully exiting a previous SPAC[3] =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but the SPARC spin could be an interesting variant, one that lets =
them launch a new vehicle automatically and without=C2=A0having to raise mo=
ney for it up front.Pershing Square=E2=80=99s SPARC will have a nominal val=
ue of $4 billion, same as its SPAC, but there=E2=80=99s no reason it has to=
 be that way; if you do a $1 billion SPAC and spin a SPARC out of it, it co=
uld be a $500 million SPARC or a $2 billion SPARC or whatever. Actually you=
 could spin out=C2=A0multiple SPARCs; why not? =E2=80=9CWhen this deal clos=
es, investors will get the SPAC deal they were originally promised, plus ri=
ghts to chip in $5 to one new deal, and=C2=A0$10 to another new deal, and $=
20 to a third new deal.=E2=80=9D And then you could pursue one or two or al=
l of those new deals, and if any of them work out the rights could be exerc=
isable. And if none of them work out, who cares, it's not like the investor=
s paid for the SPARC rights.Well, they didn=E2=80=99t pay you. Presumably t=
he rights would trade on the stock market as pure bets on your success as a=
 SPAC sponsor and your continuing interest in finding a deal. (Or deals.) T=
he theory is that if holders of your old SPAC want to re-up with you, they =
can keep their SPARC rights and eventually contribute money to your next de=
al; if they don=E2=80=99t, they can sell their SPARC rights to someone who=
=C2=A0does=C2=A0want to bet on your next deal. The rights end up in the han=
ds of enthusiasts for your work, and then when you announce a deal those en=
thusiasts can fund it.=C2=A0All of this assumes that you=E2=80=99ve already=
 got a SPAC going and that it=E2=80=99s closing in on a merger. What if you=
 don=E2=80=99t? Well,=C2=A0you could spin SPARC rights out of something els=
e. Public companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0banks, private equity firms, SoftBank, e=
tc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0 sometimes sponsor SPACs in the regular way; I suppose t=
hey could spin SPARCs=C2=A0to their shareholders directly out of the public=
 company. The shareholders would get the SPARC rights for free, as a fun li=
ttle bonus, and then could either keep them (as a chance to co-invest with =
the company if it finds a deal) or sell them in the market for a bit of cas=
h.All of these things assume that you give the SPARC rights away=C2=A0for f=
ree. They might be worth something =E2=80=94=C2=A0they will have some marke=
t price, as bets on your ability to find a good deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it =
would be unseemly for=C2=A0you=C2=A0to charge for them. Could you, though? =
Could you just=C2=A0sell=C2=A0the SPARC rights directly to potential invest=
ors? Could you launch a SPARC not with a free distribution to existing shar=
eholders of something (a SPAC, a SPARC, a public company), but with an init=
ial public offering of the rights for cash?Seems =E2=80=A6=C2=A0aggressive.=
 The thing you are selling is =E2=80=9CI will try to find a deal, and if I =
find one I will ask you to pay for it.=E2=80=9D Doesn=E2=80=99t seem like i=
t should be worth anything, and in fact the standard price for that part of=
 a SPAC is zero dollars. A SPAC sponsor asks investors to chip in $10, for =
which they get (1) an expectation that the sponsor will try to find a deal,=
 and the right to contribute to it if she finds one, plus (2) a $10 money-m=
arket investment. If you invest $10, you get the bet on the sponsor, plus $=
10; the bet on the sponsor is thus free. It might be worth more than zero =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the SPAC might trade above $10 before it announces a deal =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but the sponsor won=E2=80=99t charge more than zero for it.=
=C2=A0The Securities and Exchange Commission has rules to protect the inves=
tors in a SPAC, to make sure that they can get their money back; doing a pa=
id SPARC offering would probably go a bit too far. Still I would like to se=
e someone try.A correctionSpeaking of Pershing Square Tontine Holdings, Fri=
day=E2=80=99s Money Stuff included an error in the calculation of the cash =
value of PSTH Remainco, one of the three bits that PSTH is splitting into. =
I said it was $7.50 per share, but really it=E2=80=99s $5.25 per share, for=
 reasons explained in  footnote 3 of the corrected column. The $5.25, added=
 to the $14.75 value that Pershing Square attributes to the shares of Unive=
rsal Music Group BV that it will distribute to investors, totals $20, which=
 was the cash value that investors originally put into PSTH. Sorry.


