Hedge-fund hiringOne interpretation of the efficient markets hypothesis is =
that it means that no hedge fund should be able to pick stocks that beat th=
e market reliably over a long period of time. In fact some hedge funds do s=
eem to be able to do this, so that interpretation of the efficient markets =
hypothesis is probably not quite correct. You could however have various th=
eories of market meta-efficiency. Like: =E2=80=9CSome hedge funds can relia=
bly beat the market, but you will not be able to identify which ones they a=
re.=E2=80=9D Or: =E2=80=9CSome hedge funds can reliably beat the market, bu=
t they are not accepting new money from the likes of you.=E2=80=9D Or: =E2=
=80=9CSome hedge funds can reliably beat the market, but they will charge t=
heir entire alpha, or more, in fees, so that your investment in them won=E2=
=80=99t reliably beat the market.=E2=80=9D None of these are quite right, b=
ut they all have a certain truth to them. The fact that someone can do magi=
c doesn=E2=80=99t mean that they=E2=80=99ll do it for you.Or, again, one in=
terpretation of the EMH is =E2=80=9Cno=C2=A0person=C2=A0can pick stocks tha=
t beat the market reliably over a long period of time,=E2=80=9D and again t=
hat seems not to be true, but you could believe a=C2=A0meta version like =
=E2=80=9Csome people can pick stocks that beat the market reliably over a l=
ong period of time, but you will not be able to identify who they are in ad=
vance.=E2=80=9D Or: =E2=80=9CBut they have better things to do than work fo=
r you.=E2=80=9DHere is a fun Financial Times profile of Julian Robertson=E2=
=80=99s famous old hedge fund Tiger Management, which closed in 2000 but wh=
ose employees went on to found lots of other successful hedge funds. It is =
interesting that, for 20 years,=C2=A0Robertson was usually good at buying s=
tocks that went up. But it is more impressive that he was good at hiring pe=
ople who turned out to be good at buying stocks that went up:Robertson told=
 the FT that a rigorous hiring process was key: =E2=80=9CI think they were =
talented people and we went after them in a very deliberate and planned way=
,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThey were really picked very carefully.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0Sure sure sure, but everyone would say that; no hedge-fund manager=
 would be like =E2=80=9Cmeh we just hire whoever, I hired my tennis coach t=
o be a stock analyst, this job isn=E2=80=99t hard.=E2=80=9D The point is no=
t that Tiger, uniquely, tried very hard to hire good stock-pickers; the poi=
nt is that Tiger had unusual success at it. Also that it hired=C2=A0a psych=
oanalyst to make a test for good stock-pickers:A key player in that process=
 was Dr Aaron Stern, a psychoanalyst who worked in various roles at the fir=
m including chief operating officer for 30 years. Dr Stern, who died in Apr=
il aged 96, was a leading expert in narcissistic personality disorder and w=
rote the influential 1979 book Me: The Narcissistic American.I wonder if he=
 wrote a revised and expanded edition=C2=A0after working at a hedge fund, h=
ey-o!=C2=A0Anyway:Robertson used Dr Stern in the early 1990s to develop a s=
ystematic way of replicating Tiger Management=E2=80=99s early success hirin=
g talented young analysts, which had until then relied on Robertson=E2=80=
=99s gut instinct. The test for applicants consisted of about 450 questions=
 and lasted over three hours.=E2=80=9CHe was very important because he real=
ly did perfect=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89this recruitment techn=
ique that we used,=E2=80=9D said Robertson.Questions could include the Rors=
chach test, developed in 1921 for spotting mental imbalances. Stern also de=
signed the exams so applicants could not =E2=80=98game=E2=80=99 them by giv=
ing answers they thought Tiger wanted.=E2=80=9CSome of the questions were o=
pen-ended,=E2=80=9D said one former portfolio manager who took the test. =
=E2=80=9CIt was along the lines of: Is it more important to get on well wit=
h your team or to challenge them? Would you prefer to be intellectually rig=
ht but lose money or to be intellectually wrong but save the trade?=E2=80=
=9DI guess I would prefer to be intellectually right but lose money, which =
is (part of) why I=E2=80=99m a blogger and not a Tiger Cub, but I assume th=
at=E2=80=99s the wrong answer. I don=E2=80=99t know though! I=E2=80=99m fas=
cinated by the test. Did they validate it? Is there some vault somewhere wi=
th the Stern test scores of every Tiger Management applicant that you can c=
orrelate with their subsequent investing track records? That=E2=80=99s a da=
ta set that will get you tenure.Also, though, a big theme in modern investi=
ng is replacing the stock-picking instincts of human hedge-fund managers wi=
th machine learning. What about replacing the hiring=C2=A0instincts of huma=
n hedge-fund managers (or psychoanalysts) with machine learning? Write a 45=
0-question test, have a bunch of college grads take it, hire them randomly,=
 let your computer see which answers correlate with stock-picking success, =
iterate,=C2=A0have the computer rewrite the test, etc., until the computer =
can predict=C2=A0exactly who=E2=80=99ll pick the best stocks and then hire =
them itself. Instead of a hedge fund with a human manager relying on a comp=
uter to pick the stocks, you can have a hedge fund with a computer manager =
relying on humans to pick the stocks.Meme indexingThere are three important=
 tiers of U.S. stock indexes. The lowest is the Russell 2000 index of small=
-cap stocks, made up of, roughly speaking, the 2,000 smallest of the 3,000 =
biggest U.S. companies. The middle tier is the Russell 1000, made up of, ro=
ughly speaking, the 1,000 biggest U.S. companies. The top tier is the S&P 5=
00, made up of, roughly speaking, the 500 biggest U.S. companies.These inde=
xes are adjusted every so often; new members are added and others are dropp=
ed. The indexes=C2=A0are based on market capitalization, meaning, essential=
ly, on share price: A company is a big company if its shares are collective=
ly worth a lot of money, or a small company if they=E2=80=99re worth less. =
So if you have a small company and its stock goes up a lot, it will move fr=
om the small-cap index to a larger-cap index.Sometimes this is self-reinfor=
cing. The S&P 500 is a more popular large-cap index than the Russell 1000.[=
4] When a company moves into the S&P 500, all the S&P 500 index-fund manage=
rs buy it. Also it stays in the Russell 1000, so no Russell 1000 index-fund=
 managers sell it.=C2=A0The result is that there=E2=80=99s added buying pre=
ssure from index funds and the stock often goes up.=C2=A0So the stock goes =
up to get into the bigger index, and then getting into the bigger index cau=
ses it to go up more.Other times, though, it works the other way. The Russe=
ll 2000 is a popular small-cap index; the Russell 1000 is not an especially=
 popular large-cap index. (The popular large-cap index is the S&P 500.) If =
you want to own =E2=80=9Call the big stocks,=E2=80=9D you buy the S&P 500; =
if you want to own =E2=80=9Call the small-cap stocks,=E2=80=9D you buy the =
Russell 2000; there is less of a natural constituency for the Russell 1000.=
 So less money is indexed to it.[5] And (unlike the S&P 500 and Russell 100=
0) the Russell 1000 and Russell 2000 do not overlap: If a company moves out=
 of the Russell 2000 into the Russell 1000, Russell 1000 funds buy it, but =
Russell 2000 funds also sell it. Also its=C2=A0weighting=C2=A0will be diffe=
rent:=C2=A0The biggest stock in the Russell 2000 (Caesars Entertainment Inc=
.) has a weight of about 0.69% of the index; the smallest stock in the Russ=
ell 1000 (Ardagh Group SA) has a weight of about 0.0012%.[6]So when a compa=
ny goes from being a large small-cap to being a small large-cap, it gets a =
smaller weight in a smaller index. So indexed investors sell. So the stock =
goes up to get into the bigger index, and then getting into the bigger inde=
x causes it to go back down. Fortunately the Russell indexes only change me=
mbers once a year, so there=E2=80=99s time to recover; it=E2=80=99s not lik=
e stocks are constantly ping-ponging between the indexes.=C2=A0That said, I=
 don=E2=80=99t really buy  this:The upcoming Russell Indexes reshuffle coul=
d pose a problem for the likes of AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. and GameS=
top Corp.FTSE Russell=E2=80=99s annual Reconstitution event, which moves st=
ocks around in its U.S. indexes based on their updated market cap and other=
 characteristics, is set to call attention once again to the rise in so-cal=
led meme stocks that have been favorites of the retail-trading crowd.AMC is=
 up more than 2,100% this year and GameStop over 1,200% -- with commensurat=
e increases to their weighting in the Russell 2000 small-cap stock index. T=
he two together now make up more than 1.1% of that gauge. But their enlarge=
d market caps, with AMC at $24.6 billion and GameStop at $18.4 billion, put=
 them squarely in line for a move to the Russell 1000 index of the biggest =
American companies.=E2=80=9CThe graduation of these high-fliers could be th=
e beginning of the end of their epic run,=E2=80=9D Wells Fargo analysts Chr=
istopher Harvey, Gary Liebowitz and Anna Han wrote in a note Friday.My gut =
instinct is that AMC and GameStop are not going to be slowed down by a few =
index funds selling their stocks. Lots of active funds dumped their stocks =
during their run-ups! Lots of hedge funds shorted their stocks! The wildly =
enthusiastic retail buyers took this as a challenge and bid the stocks up e=
ven more. The idea that some boring index reconstitution will end the fun i=
n the meme stocks just doesn=E2=80=99t fit with how meme stocks work.=C2=A0=
To be fair, the list of top GameStop shareholders is a hilarious ghost town=
; the top 10 list includes the Big Three index-fund managers, insiders like=
 Ryan Cohen (the board chairman) and George Sherman, and, in=C2=A0fourth pl=
ace, Susquehanna International Group, the big options market maker: When th=
ousands=C2=A0of retail investors  buy GameStop call options to push up the =
price, Susquehanna is often on the other side, and it hedges those options =
by being one of=C2=A0GameStop=E2=80=99s biggest shareholders. AMC=E2=80=99s=
 holders list is also pretty bare, and the company=C2=A0announced last week=
 that 80% of its shares are held by retail investors.=C2=A0Still there is r=
oom for pruning; as of right now, boring old BlackRock Inc. is technically =
GameStop=E2=80=99s largest shareholder, while boring old Vanguard Group is =
AMC=E2=80=99s. During GameStop=E2=80=99s run in January,  most of its profe=
ssional actively managed shareholders dumped their stock, but there are sti=
ll some professionals still involved. If GameStop and AMC move into the Rus=
sell 1000, the result might be that their few remaining institutional inves=
tors =E2=80=94=C2=A0the index funds =E2=80=94 will sell some shares, and th=
ey will become even more purely the playthings of excited retail investors.=
Elsewhere: =E2=80=9CAMC Drama Is  Exposing Risks in $11 Trillion World of I=
ndexing.=E2=80=9D The risk of indexing is that, when you buy an index fund,=
 you are buying all the stocks at their market prices! The risk is that som=
etimes the market prices are too high and later they go down! I dunno, this=
 does not trouble me very much. My money is in index funds and I have alway=
s been cool with this risk. When you pick your own stocks, sometimes they g=
o down too.Invisible sculptureI take it as inevitable that people will star=
t selling =E2=80=9Cnon-fungible tokens=E2=80=9D that don=E2=80=99t live on =
a blockchain or make use of cryptocurrency technology. Like:=09I buy a Pica=
sso.=09I light it on fire.=09I write up a receipt saying =E2=80=9CI sure li=
t that Picasso on fire.=E2=80=9D=09 That=E2=80=99s an =E2=80=9CNFT.=E2=80=
=9D=09I sell you the NFT for more than I paid for the Picasso.In=C2=A0step =
3 of a typical NFT,=C2=A0the receipt lives on a blockchain, and obviously t=
he blockchain part of it appeals to crypto millionaires and maybe allows me=
 to sell it for more money. But that does not seem particularly essential t=
o the artistic or commercial transaction. If I just printed the receipt on =
nice paper and signed it with a pen, that=E2=80=99s a =E2=80=9Cnon-fungible=
 token=E2=80=9D too. Who cares.Here=E2=80=99s=C2=A0an analog NFT:An Italian=
 artist sold an invisible sculpture for over $18,000 and had to give the bu=
yer a certificate of authenticity to prove it=E2=80=99s real, the Daily Mai=
l reported.Salvatore Garau sold his piece, entitled =E2=80=9CIo Sono=E2=80=
=9D (I am), to an unidentified buyer last month. ...=E2=80=9CThe vacuum is =
nothing more than a space full of energy, and even if we empty it and there=
 is nothing left, according to the Heisenberg uncertainty principle, that =
=E2=80=98nothing=E2=80=99 has a weight,=E2=80=9D the Sardinian-born artist =
explained, according to Hypebeast. =E2=80=9CTherefore, it has energy that i=
s condensed and transformed into particles, that is, into us.=E2=80=9DThe 6=
7-year-old explained in a video that =E2=80=9Cyou don=E2=80=99t see it but =
it exists; it is made of air and spirit.=E2=80=9DI cannot emphasize this en=
ough: Sure, whatever.[7] Though $18,000 seems a little low. If he=E2=80=99d=
 put the certificate on an NFT platform some crypto whale would have paid h=
im a million dollars for it. Still that seems like a failure of imagination=
. If you=E2=80=99re a crypto art collector, it is all well and good to coll=
ect digital pointers to nothing and tell people =E2=80=9Coooh look at my NF=
T collection oooh,=E2=80=9D but wouldn=E2=80=99t it be more exciting to thr=
ow in some analog NFTs for variety? =E2=80=9CIn this room of my imaginary h=
ouse I have my OpenSea NFTs, over here in the imaginary foyer are the Found=
ation NFTs, and then here in the imaginary library are my rare primitive pa=
per NFTs.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Any=C2=A0crypto millionaire can buy NFTs on the blo=
ckchain; it takes a discerning eye to buy them on paper.=C2=A0Anyway,  as I=
  often  say, the most popular=C2=A0way to generate NFTs is by taking exist=
ing physical works of art, lighting them on fire, and selling a receipt to =
your customer. I suppose someone could NFT this invisible sculpture that wa=
y. Hire a mime with an invisible sledgehammer to destroy the invisible scul=
pture, film the whole thing, sell a YouTube video of it on the blockchain. =
Actually I may do that myself. How do you know that I didn=E2=80=99t sneak =
into the buyer=E2=80=99s house and steal the invisible sculpture that I am =
now invisibly destroying with my invisible sledgehammer? Sure I don=E2=80=
=99t have the receipt for the sculpture, but an NFT of me illicitly destroy=
ing a stolen invisible sculpture is even more daring and transgressive and =
artistic than one of me destroying an invisible=C2=A0sculpture I bought, ri=
ght?Things happenJeff Bezos Says  He=E2=80=99ll Travel to Space on Blue Ori=
gin Flight. Medline Deal Signals Return to Days of Huge Leveraged Buyouts.=
=C2=A0Yellen Says  Higher Interest Rates Would Be =E2=80=98Plus=E2=80=99 fo=
r U.S., Fed. Financial groups dash to raise short-term funding in US on the=
 cheap. El Salvador looks to become the world=E2=80=99s first country to ad=
opt bitcoin as legal tender. Thousands Descend on Miami to Glorify Bitcoin.=
=C2=A0Crypto Frauds Target Investors Hoping to Cash In on Bitcoin Boom. Aft=
er Pressure,  All-Male Boards Have Now Vanished From S&P 500. Businesses Br=
ace for More Climate Cases After Ruling on Shell Emissions. US troops accid=
entally storm olive oil factory in Bulgaria.=C2=A0After Years Of Detecting =
Land Mines, A Heroic Rat Is Hanging Up His Sniffer.If you'd like to get=C2=
=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, please=
=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other=
 great Bloomberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] In other ways it is a worse p=
roduct for investors: The SPAC=E2=80=99s pool-of-cash-plus-warrants structu=
re is what=C2=A0makes it attractive to hedge funds, creating some free mone=
y by combining a money-market sure-to-be-worth-$10 instrument with a valuab=
le warrant and selling the package for $10. In *other* other ways, that mag=
ical free value for hedge funds can be bad for ordinary investors in the SP=
AC.[2] Actually he=E2=80=99ll be hunting for a $5.6 billion to $10.6 billio=
n deal. That consists of (1) $4 billion notional=C2=A0of SPARC rights held =
by current public shareholders in Pershing Square Tontine Holdings, (2) $1.=
6 billion notional of SPARC rights that will be held by Pershing Square fun=
ds that will invest cash in PSTH before the SPARC distribution, and (3) a f=
orward commitment from Pershing Square funds to invest $1 billion to $5 bil=
lion alongside the SPARC. I am using $4 billion in the text to focus on the=
 money Ackman is quasi-raising from public investors, but his hedge fund=C2=
=A0will put in a lot of money alongside the public investors in any eventua=
l deal.[3] Or before successfully exiting, of course. The top SPAC sponsors=
 often have several SPACs going at a time.[4] For instance, the iShares Cor=
e S&P 500 exchange-traded fund (IVV), BlackRock=E2=80=99s main S&P 500 ETF,=
 has about $282 billion of assets under management; the iShares Russell 100=
0 ETF (IWB) has about $29 billion.[5] For instance, the iShares Russell 100=
0 ETF (IWB) has about $29 billion of assets under management; the iShares R=
ussell 2000 ETF (IWM) has about $67.4 billion.=C2=A0[6] I don=E2=80=99t rea=
lly mean =E2=80=9Cbiggest=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Csmallest,=E2=80=9D just hig=
hest and lowest weightings on Bloomberg=E2=80=99s list of index constituent=
s. Those weightings should correspond to float-adjusted market cap at the t=
ime of the last index rebalancing, not to current market cap.=C2=A0[7] Amon=
g other things, Yves Klein was doing this bit in 1959, calling it a =E2=80=
=9Czone=C2=A0de sensibilit=C3=A9 picturale immat=C3=A9rielle.=E2=80=9D From=
 Wikipedia: =E2=80=9CThe work involved the sale of documentation of ownersh=
ip of empty space (the Immaterial Zone), taking the form of a receipt, in e=
xchange for gold; if the buyer wished, the piece could then be completed in=
 an elaborate ritual in which the buyer would burn the receipt, and Klein w=
ould throw half of the gold into the Seine. The ritual would be performed i=
n the presence of an art critic or distinguished dealer, an art museum dire=
ctor and at least two witnesses.=E2=80=9D
