<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top=
: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">SPARC SPARC SPARC</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24078835.263=
647/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDQ=
vYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4tcy1zcGFjLXdpbGwtYmUtdGhyZWUtc3BhY3M/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB0a80f967" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> talked on Friday</a> about Pershing Square Tontine Holdings Ltd., Bill =
Ackman=E2=80=99s special purpose acquisition vehicle, which will fission in=
to three SPAC-like things: It will do a somewhat SPAC-ish deal with Univers=
al Music Group BV and distribute Universal shares to its investors, it will=
 keep some cash around in a =E2=80=9CRemainco=E2=80=9D that will try to do =
another acquisition, and, most interestingly, it will emit a SPARC. Pershin=
g Square <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24078835.=
263647/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4MTE4ODIvMDAw=
MTE5MzEyNTIxMTgxOTQyL2QxNzI3MjFkZXg5OTEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8131e=
e42" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">expla=
ins</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SPARC is not a SPAC. I=
t is a Special Purpose Acquisition Rights Company. Unlike a traditional SPA=
C, SPARC does not intend to raise capital through an underwritten offering =
in which investors commit capital without knowing the company with which SP=
ARC will combine.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, SPARC intends to=
 issue rights to acquire common stock in SPARC for $20.00 per share to PSTH=
 shareholders (=E2=80=9CSPARs=E2=80=9D) which can only be exercised after S=
PARC enters into a definitive agreement for its initial business combinatio=
n.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Pershing Square Tontine Hol=
dings will distribute the SPARs =E2=80=94=C2=A0the SPARC rights =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0to its existing shareholders, so they can have first dibs on the next=
 big deal that Ackman does. As I said on Friday, this strikes me as a cool =
idea. For one thing, it is in some ways a better product, for investors, th=
an a SPAC: Instead of locking up money for up to two years while a SPAC hun=
ts for a deal (and then maybe taking it back if they don=E2=80=99t like the=
 deal), SPARC investors don=E2=80=99t put up any money until the SPARC find=
s a deal.[1]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For another thing, though, rig=
ht now is kind of a hard time to raise money for a SPAC: There are a lot of=
 SPACs, there is a lot of money tied up in them, a lot of them have not tra=
ded that well, and there is a general sense that the early-2021 frenzy for =
SPACs left the market oversaturated. The Pershing Square SPARC lets Ackman =
go out and hunt for a $4 billion deal=C2=A0without raising $4 billion, <em>=
yet</em>.[2] If he finds a company he likes, he can say =E2=80=9Cwell I=C2=
=A0<em>more or less</em>=C2=A0have a $4 billion pool of capital here.=E2=80=
=9D And then he can negotiate a deal and=C2=A0go to the SPARC holders for m=
oney, and if they like the deal they=E2=80=99ll give it to him.=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say you agree with me, and Ackman,=
 that the SPARC is a good idea, and you want to launch one. How do you do t=
hat? Ackman is doing it as part of this fissioning of PSTH: He already has =
a $4 billion SPAC, and he=E2=80=99s going to turn it into a $4 billion SPAR=
C plus some other stuff (Universal, Remainco). If=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0</em>al=
so already have a SPAC, you could probably turn it into a SPARC too. I mean=
, probably best to fission it into a SPAC deal=C2=A0<em>plus</em>=C2=A0a SP=
ARC, like Ackman is doing, though yours doesn=E2=80=99t have to be so compl=
icated. Like:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px;=
 margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have a SPAC.</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The SPAC does a regular SPAC deal, a =
=E2=80=9Cde-SPAC merger=E2=80=9D in which it merges with some private compa=
ny to take it public.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The SPAC say=
s =E2=80=9Cwhen this SPAC deal closes, investors in the SPAC will get (1) s=
hares of the new public company that results from the SPAC deal=C2=A0<em>pl=
us=C2=A0</em>(2) one right in my new SPARC.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">The SPAC closes, the new public company does its thing, =
and the new SPARC exists and trades.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">Eventually the SPARC finds another deal, goes to its rights holders and =
says =E2=80=9Cokay do you want to put in your money now?=E2=80=9D</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If they do, the SPARC closes another deal.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Might as well spin=C2=A0a new SPAR=
C out of that one too.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Etc.</li></=
ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, the SPARC works as sort of a chain=
-SPARCing mechanism: You raise a SPAC, and when the SPAC terminates in a su=
ccessful deal you spin out a new SPARC; when that terminates in a successfu=
l deal it spins out another SPARC; etc. Plenty of serial SPAC sponsors do s=
omething like this =E2=80=94=C2=A0raise a new SPAC after successfully exiti=
ng a previous SPAC[3] =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the SPARC spin could be an interes=
ting variant, one that lets them launch a new vehicle automatically and wit=
hout<em>=C2=A0</em>having to raise money for it up front.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Pershing Square=E2=80=99s SPARC will have a nominal value of=
 $4 billion, same as its SPAC, but there=E2=80=99s no reason it has to be t=
hat way; if you do a $1 billion SPAC and spin a SPARC out of it, it could b=
e a $500 million SPARC or a $2 billion SPARC or whatever. Actually you coul=
d spin out=C2=A0<em>multiple </em>SPARCs; why not? =E2=80=9CWhen this deal =
closes, investors will get the SPAC deal they were originally promised, plu=
s rights to chip in $5 to one new deal, and=C2=A0$10 to another new deal, a=
nd $20 to a third new deal.=E2=80=9D And then you could pursue one or two o=
r all of those new deals, and if any of them work out the rights could be e=
xercisable. And if none of them work out, who cares, it's not like the inve=
stors paid for the SPARC rights.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, they=
 didn=E2=80=99t pay you. Presumably the rights would trade on the stock mar=
ket as pure bets on your success as a SPAC sponsor and your continuing inte=
rest in finding a deal. (Or deals.) The theory is that if holders of your o=
ld SPAC want to re-up with you, they can keep their SPARC rights and eventu=
ally contribute money to your next deal; if they don=E2=80=99t, they can se=
ll their SPARC rights to someone who=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>want to bet on=
 your next deal. The rights end up in the hands of enthusiasts for your wor=
k, and then when you announce a deal those enthusiasts can fund it.=C2=A0</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of this assumes that you=E2=80=99ve alre=
ady got a SPAC going and that it=E2=80=99s closing in on a merger. What if =
you don=E2=80=99t? Well,=C2=A0you could spin SPARC rights out of something =
else. Public companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0banks, private equity firms, SoftBank=
, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0 sometimes sponsor SPACs in the regular way; I suppos=
e they could spin SPARCs=C2=A0to their shareholders directly out of the pub=
lic company. The shareholders would get the SPARC rights for free, as a fun=
 little bonus, and then could either keep them (as a chance to co-invest wi=
th the company if it finds a deal) or sell them in the market for a bit of =
cash.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of these things assume that you g=
ive the SPARC rights away=C2=A0<em>for free</em>. They might be worth somet=
hing =E2=80=94=C2=A0they will have some market price, as bets on your abili=
ty to find a good deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it would be unseemly for=C2=A0<em=
>you=C2=A0</em>to charge for them. Could you, though? Could you just=C2=A0<=
em>sell=C2=A0</em>the SPARC rights directly to potential investors? Could y=
ou launch a SPARC not with a free distribution to existing shareholders of =
something (a SPAC, a SPARC, a public company), but with an initial public o=
ffering of the rights for cash?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Seems =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0aggressive. The thing you are selling is =E2=80=9CI will try to=
 find a deal, and if I find one I will ask you to pay for it.=E2=80=9D Does=
n=E2=80=99t seem like it should be worth anything, and in fact the standard=
 price for that part of a SPAC is zero dollars. A SPAC sponsor asks investo=
rs to chip in $10, for which they get (1) an expectation that the sponsor w=
ill try to find a deal, and the right to contribute to it if she finds one,=
 plus (2) a $10 money-market investment. If you invest $10, you get the bet=
 on the sponsor, <em>plus $10</em>; the bet on the sponsor is thus free. It=
 might be worth more than zero =E2=80=94=C2=A0the SPAC might trade above $1=
0 before it announces a deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the sponsor won=E2=80=99t c=
harge more than zero for it.=C2=A0The Securities and Exchange Commission ha=
s rules to protect the investors in a SPAC, to make sure that they can get =
their money back; doing a paid SPARC offering would probably go a bit too f=
ar. Still I would like to see someone try.</p><h2 style=3D"font-weight: bol=
d; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; lett=
er-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">A =
correction</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Speaking of Pershing Square Ton=
tine Holdings, Friday=E2=80=99s Money Stuff included an error in the calcul=
ation of the cash value of PSTH Remainco, one of the three bits that PSTH i=
s splitting into. I said it was $7.50 per share, but really it=E2=80=99s $5=
.25 per share, for reasons explained in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/24078835.263647/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDQvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4tcy1zcGFjLXdpbGwtYmUtdGhy=
ZWUtc3BhY3MjZm9vdG5vdGUtMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB940a65ac" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> footnote 3 of the corr=
ected column</a>. The $5.25, added to the $14.75 value that Pershing Square=
 attributes to the shares of Universal Music Group BV that it will distribu=
te to investors, totals $20, which was the cash value that investors origin=
ally put into PSTH. Sorry.</p>
