<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top=
: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">Hedge-fund hiring</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">One interpretation of the efficient markets hypothesis is that it means =
that no hedge fund should be able to pick stocks that beat the market relia=
bly over a long period of time. In fact some hedge funds do seem to be able=
 to do this, so that interpretation of the efficient markets hypothesis is =
probably not quite correct. You could however have various theories of mark=
et meta-efficiency. Like: =E2=80=9CSome hedge funds can reliably beat the m=
arket, but you will not be able to identify which ones they are.=E2=80=9D O=
r: =E2=80=9CSome hedge funds can reliably beat the market, but they are not=
 accepting new money from the likes of you.=E2=80=9D Or: =E2=80=9CSome hedg=
e funds can reliably beat the market, but they will charge their entire alp=
ha, or more, in fees, so that your investment in them won=E2=80=99t reliabl=
y beat the market.=E2=80=9D None of these are quite right, but they all hav=
e a certain truth to them. The fact that someone can do magic doesn=E2=80=
=99t mean that they=E2=80=99ll do it for you.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Or, again, one interpretation of the EMH is =E2=80=9Cno=C2=A0<em>person=
=C2=A0</em>can pick stocks that beat the market reliably over a long period=
 of time,=E2=80=9D and again that seems not to be true, but you could belie=
ve a=C2=A0meta version like =E2=80=9Csome people can pick stocks that beat =
the market reliably over a long period of time, but you will not be able to=
 identify who they are in advance.=E2=80=9D Or: =E2=80=9CBut they have bett=
er things to do than work for you.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24078835.=
263647/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZTFkMWM1NTgtOWE4Ny00ODQzLTljZDgt=
MjlhYjIwM2I3OTEx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4a56d1ba" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a fun Financial Times profile</a>=
 of Julian Robertson=E2=80=99s famous old hedge fund Tiger Management, whic=
h closed in 2000 but whose employees went on to found lots of other success=
ful hedge funds. It is interesting that, for 20 years,=C2=A0Robertson was u=
sually good at buying stocks that went up. But it is more impressive that h=
e was good at hiring people who turned out to be good at buying stocks that=
 went up:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Robertson told the FT=
 that a rigorous hiring process was key: =E2=80=9CI think they were talente=
d people and we went after them in a very deliberate and planned way,=E2=80=
=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThey were really picked very carefully.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sure sure sure, but everyo=
ne would say that; no hedge-fund manager would be like =E2=80=9Cmeh we just=
 hire whoever, I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2=
4078835.263647/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3NpbnNpZGVyLmNvbS90ZWFjaC1iaWxsLWFj=
a21hbi1hLXNwb3J0LWFuZC1oZS1taWdodC1oaXJlLXlvdS0yMDEyLTU/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB40beb776" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">hired my tennis coach</a> to be a stock analyst, this job isn=E2=80=
=99t hard.=E2=80=9D The point is not that Tiger, uniquely, tried very hard =
to hire good stock-pickers; the point is that Tiger had unusual success at =
it. Also that it hired=C2=A0a psychoanalyst to make a test for good stock-p=
